<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-07-30T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-07-30T06:00:00-05:00" n="457" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d457">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/7541: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-07-30T19:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">July 30,
                                        1926—7 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received July 31—12:56
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>311. Legation’s 304, July 26, noon. Following telegram has been received
                            from the American consul general at Canton: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“July 29, 2 p.m. Referring to telegram of July 23, noon.
                                    Cantonese authorities now predict capture of Hankow and Wuchang
                                    in 10 days. General Chiang of Whampoa Cadets has left Canton for
                                    the Hunan front.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>